wiki_catalogs.name: Project Overview
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the vandamme-proxy project. Explain its purpose as a universal LLM gateway that enables seamless integration across multiple AI providers (OpenAI, Anthropic, Poe, Azure, Gemini, AWS Bedrock) with protocol translation, smart model aliasing, and secure API key passthrough. Document the architectural vision of unifying diverse LLM interfaces under a single, consistent API surface. Highlight key benefits such as reduced integration complexity, enhanced observability via the built-in dashboard, and flexible routing capabilities. Include high-level diagrams showing the request flow from client to upstream provider through the proxy. Provide real-world use cases like A/B testing models, failover strategies, and cost optimization. Use terminology consistent with the codebase such as 'provider routing', 'alias resolution', and 'thought signature'. Introduce core components like the middleware chain, conversion layer, and dashboard without deep technical detailsave those for dedicated sections. Make this accessible to beginners while giving experienced developers a strategic understanding of the system's value proposition.

wiki_catalogs.name: Configuration Hierarchy
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the configuration hierarchy. Explain the three-tiered configuration system that combines environment variables (highest priority), TOML configuration files (medium priority), and hardcoded defaults (lowest priority). Detail the loading order and merge strategy as implemented in AliasConfigLoader, showing how local project configurations override user-level settings, which in turn override package defaults. Document the specific file paths searched: ./vandamme-config.toml, ~/.config/vandamme-proxy/vandamme-config.toml, and src/config/defaults.toml. Illustrate with examples how configuration values are resolved and overridden at each level. Use code examples from src/core/alias_config.py to demonstrate the load_config method's merging logic and caching behavior. Explain the implications of configuration precedence on production deployments and development workflows.

Include configuration via environment variables and .env files, referencing .env.example. Detail the use of Makefile workflows for development tasks like running the server, checking health, and validating installation. Address common issues such as missing uv binary, incorrect Python version, and dependency conflicts. Include examples of starting the server with custom host and port settings.

<blog>
# Vandamme Proxy: Comprehensive Project Overview

## 1. Project Introduction

### Purpose Statement
Vandamme Proxy is a sophisticated LLM gateway designed to transform Claude Code (or any Anthropic API client) into a multi-provider client that supports OpenAI, Anthropic, Poe, Azure, Gemini, and other compatible APIs. It serves as a universal interface for AI development workflows, enabling seamless integration across multiple LLM providers.

### Core Goals and Objectives
- **Multi-Provider Support**: Enable routing to various LLM providers through a single interface
- **Protocol Compatibility**: Support both OpenAI conversion and native Anthropic passthrough
- **Developer Experience**: Provide intuitive CLI tools and comprehensive dashboard monitoring
- **Enterprise Features**: Implement secure API key management, multi-tenancy, and production-ready observability

### Target Audience
- AI developers using Claude Code CLI who want multi-provider flexibility
- Engineering teams requiring production-grade LLM gateways
- Organizations needing secure, multi-tenant AI infrastructure
- Developers seeking intelligent model routing and aliasing capabilities

## 2. Technical Architecture

### Component Breakdown
Vandamme Proxy follows a modular architecture with clear separation of concerns:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Client Applications] --> B[API Gateway]
    B --> C[Smart Alias Engine]
    B --> D[Provider Router]
    C --> D
    D --> E[OpenAI Format Handler]
    D --> F[Anthropic Passthrough]
    E --> G[OpenAI API]
    F --> H[Anthropic API]
    F --> I[Poe API]
    F --> J[Azure/Gemini]
    B --> K[Dashboard UI]
    B --> L[Metrics & Monitoring]
    M[Configuration] --> B
    N[CLI Tools] --> B
```

### Design Patterns
The system implements several key architectural patterns:

- **Chain-of-Responsibility**: Middleware system for request/response processing
- **Factory Pattern**: Dynamic provider creation based on environment variables
- **Singleton Pattern**: Configuration management with hierarchical overrides
- **Observer Pattern**: Real-time dashboard updates via SSE (Server-Sent Events)

### System Relationships
The architecture demonstrates a clean separation between core functionality and extended features:

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Main Application] --> B[API Layer]
    A --> C[Core Services]
    A --> D[Dashboard]
    A --> E[CLI Interface]
    B --> F[Request Processing]
    C --> G[Configuration]
    C --> H[Provider Management]
    C --> I[Model Aliasing]
    D --> J[Data Visualization]
    E --> K[Server Management]
    E --> L[Health Checks]
    F --> M[Format Conversion]
    M --> N[OpenAI  Anthropic]
```

### Data Flow
The request processing pipeline follows a well-defined sequence:

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    Client[Client Request] --> Gateway[API Gateway]
    Gateway --> Alias[Smart Alias Resolution]
    Alias --> Router[Provider Router]
    Router --> Format[Format Selection]
    Format -->|OpenAI| Converter[OpenAI Conversion]
    Format -->|Anthropic| Passthrough[Direct Passthrough]
    Converter --> Upstream[Upstream Provider]
    Passthrough --> Upstream
    Upstream --> Response[Response Processing]
    Response --> Client
```

## 3. Key Implementation

### Main Entry Points
- `src/main.py`: Primary application entry point
- `start_proxy.py`: Alternative startup script
- `src/cli/main.py`: CLI interface implementation

### Core Modules
- **API Layer**: `src/api/` - FastAPI-based endpoints and services
- **Core Services**: `src/core/` - Configuration, providers, aliases, and metrics
- **Dashboard**: `src/dashboard/` - Monitoring and visualization
- **Conversion**: `src/conversion/` - Format transformation between API standards

### Configuration Approach
The system uses a hierarchical configuration system with multiple override levels:

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Environment Variables] --> B[Local Config File]
    B --> C[User Config File]
    C --> D[Package Defaults]
    D --> E[src/config/defaults.toml]
```

Sources:
- [defaults.toml](src/config/defaults.toml)

### External Dependencies
Key dependencies from `pyproject.toml`:

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[vandamme-proxy] --> B[fastapi]
    A --> C[uvicorn]
    A --> D[pydantic]
    A --> E[python-dotenv]
    A --> F[openai]
    A --> G[respx]
    A --> H[tomli]
    A --> I[dash]
    A --> J[dash-bootstrap-components]
    A --> K[dash-ag-grid]
```

Sources:
- [pyproject.toml](pyproject.toml)

### Integration Points
The system integrates with various external services and protocols:

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[Vandamme Proxy] --> B[OpenAI API]
    A --> C[Anthropic API]
    A --> D[Poe API]
    A --> E[Azure OpenAI]
    A --> F[Google Vertex AI]
    A --> G[AWS Bedrock]
    H[Client Applications] --> A
    A --> I[Structured Logging]
    A --> J[Metrics Collection]
```

## 4. Key Features

### Functionality Overview
Vandamme Proxy offers several key features that distinguish it from alternative solutions:

- **Provider Prefix Routing**: Route requests using `provider:model` syntax
- **Smart Model Aliases**: Case-insensitive substring matching for model shortcuts
- **Dual API Format Support**: Both OpenAI conversion and Anthropic passthrough
- **Secure API Key Passthrough**: Multi-tenant deployments with client-provided keys
- **Extensible Middleware**: Chain-of-responsibility pattern for custom logic
- **Built-in Observability**: Comprehensive metrics, health checks, and logging

### Implementation Highlights
The system implements sophisticated routing and aliasing capabilities:

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Idle
    Idle --> AliasResolution: Request Received
    AliasResolution --> ProviderRouting: Alias Matched
    AliasResolution --> ProviderRouting: No Alias
    ProviderRouting --> FormatSelection: Provider Determined
    FormatSelection --> OpenAIConversion: OpenAI Format
    FormatSelection --> AnthropicPassthrough: Anthropic Format
    OpenAIConversion --> UpstreamCall
    AnthropicPassthrough --> UpstreamCall
    UpstreamCall --> ResponseProcessing
    ResponseProcessing --> ClientResponse
    ClientResponse --> Idle
```

Sources:
- [README.md](README.md#L248-L258)
- [main.py](src/main.py#L8)
- [v1.py](src/api/routers/v1.py)

### Feature Architecture
The dashboard provides real-time monitoring and management capabilities:

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Dashboard] --> B[Overview Page]
    A --> C[Metrics Page]
    A --> D[Models Page]
    A --> E[Aliases Page]
    A --> F[Token Counter]
    B --> G[Health Status]
    B --> H[KPIs]
    B --> I[Provider Status]
    C --> J[Usage Charts]
    C --> K[Active Requests]
    D --> L[Model Search]
    D --> M[Model Cards]
    E --> N[Alias Groups]
    E --> O[Mapping Rules]
    F --> P[Token Calculator]
    
    style A fill:#4B7BEC,stroke:#333
    style B fill:#5D89E8,stroke:#333
    style C fill:#5D89E8,stroke:#333
    style D fill:#5D89E8,stroke:#333
    style E fill:#5D89E8,stroke:#333
    style F fill:#5D89E8,stroke:#333
```

Sources:
- [dashboard.md](docs/dashboard.md)
- [app.py](src/dashboard/app.py)
- [overview.py](src/dashboard/callbacks/overview.py)
</blog>
